04788nam a22005895i 9780801468179DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20132013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979954147  a97808014681797 a10.7591/97808014681792doi  a(DE-B1597)478550  a(OCoLC)836207133  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aJZ6385b.W45 2016 7aHIS0270002bisacsh04a355.022231 aWeisiger, Alex, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLogics of War :bExplanations for Limited and Unlimited Conflicts /cAlex Weisiger. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b9 halftones, 5 tables, 4 charts, 2 maps, 4 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in Security Affairs00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Explanations for Limited and Unlimited Wars -- t2. Research Strategy and Statistical Tests -- t3. War to the Death in Paraguay -- t4. World War II: German Expansion and Allied Response -- t5. Additional Commitment Problem Cases: The Crimean, Pacific, and Iran-Iraq Wars -- t6. Short Wars of Optimism: Persian Gulf and Anglo-Iranian -- t7. The Limits on Leaders: The Falklands War and the Franco-Turkish War -- tConclusion: Recapitulations, Implications, and Prognostications -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMost wars between countries end quickly and at relatively low cost. The few in which high-intensity fighting continues for years bring about a disproportionate amount of death and suffering. What separates these few unusually long and intense wars from the many conflicts that are far less destructive? In Logics of War, Alex Weisiger tests three explanations for a nation's decision to go to war and continue fighting regardless of the costs. He combines sharp statistical analysis of interstate wars over the past two centuries with nine narrative case studies. He examines both well-known conflicts like World War II and the Persian Gulf War, as well as unfamiliar ones such as the 1864–1870 Paraguayan War (or the War of the Triple Alliance), which proportionally caused more deaths than any other war in modern history. When leaders go to war expecting easy victory, events usually correct their misperceptions quickly and with fairly low casualties, thereby setting the stage for a negotiated agreement. A second explanation involves motives born of domestic politics; as war becomes more intense, however, leaders are increasingly constrained in their ability to continue the fighting. Particularly destructive wars instead arise from mistrust of an opponent's intentions. Countries that launch preventive wars to forestall expected decline tend to have particularly ambitious war aims that they hold to even when fighting goes poorly. Moreover, in some cases, their opponents interpret the preventive attack as evidence of a dispositional commitment to aggression, resulting in the rejection of any form of negotiation and a demand for unconditional surrender. Weisiger’s treatment of a topic of central concern to scholars of major wars will also be read with great interest by military historians, political psychologists, and sociologists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aLimited war. 0aLow-intensity conflicts (Military science). 0aTotal war. 0aWarxCauses. 4aHistory. 4aMilitary History. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aHISTORY / Military / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9780801468179zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.de